      <header>&amp;GArmy_Rank_&amp;&amp;_File&amp;n</header>
      <slot>50</slot>
      <level>43</level>
      <author>227762</author>
      <date>1044341971</date>
      <authorname>Esbjorn</authorname>
      <text>&amp;wAt ease men. :P  As you may have noticed, I added a ghelp file entitled
'&amp;GArmy_Rank_&amp;_File&amp;w' (You need two of these '&amp;&amp;' to get it to work right if
you are bored enough to type out the whole name.)  This outlines what
each individual rank is responsible for in the Army, so if you were
wondering just what your rank meant, here is where you find that info.

Now, some of you &amp;WRules Lawyers&amp;w (you know who you are) will instantly
realize that the chain of command differs somewhat from what's outlined in
&quot;&amp;WThe World of Robert Jordan's The Wheel of Time&amp;w&quot; Well, this is for two
reasons. Firstly, I wanted to give very specific information on the
standard command tree and unit division in the Army, with which the &amp;WBWB&amp;w
(Big White Book) was not very helpful, and lastly, the chain of
command given in the &amp;WBWB&amp;w was very counterintuitive and all together
sucky.... in my opinion. :D (Ex. Bannerman being of much Higher Rank than
File Leader, while File Leaders are somewhat akin to Sergeants, and 
Bannermen are people who run around with banners.) So that's the reason
for that. :P

Also, it should be noted that the larger of these divisions are mainly in effect 
during wartime, and even then they usually only group as such on the battlefield.
The most common divisions when the Army is not on the battlefield are that of: 
&amp;WPatrols&amp;w, which patrol the streets of occupied cities and towns; &amp;WPlatoons&amp;w which 
patrol the surrounding countryside; and &amp;WCompanies&amp;w, which make small camps in 
the open field. In peacetime the Army still trains in it's larger divisions 
every so often, as to be prepared in the event of battle.

Anyway, since this file focuses more on ranking than division structure I 
think I'll add another ghelp on &amp;u&amp;WArmy Divisions&amp;n&amp;w, for clarification.&amp;n
</text>
    </message>
    <message>
      <header>More on Ranks...</header>
      <slot>51</slot>
      <level>43</level>
      <author>227762</author>
      <date>1044351064</date>
      <authorname>Esbjorn</authorname>
      <text>&amp;wI also gave the rank list a much needed cleaning, in addition to adding
and deleting some ranks. Anyone who has had their rank drasticly changed
should have recieved a mudmail from me, save all you recruits who's sub
ranks I took away.  I decided that it's too early in your training to have
to choose what route you want to take in your advancement, so your
subrank may come back upon your graduation from being a recruit.

Also, I'd like to clear something up about the Bannerman rank.  It is
now an elective rank, that means that you &amp;Wdo not&amp;w have to achieve
that rank to advance through the Army's promotion ladder. The Bannerman
rank is something that you apply for as a Soldier, and is given 
out, or not, with the factors of IC merit and availability in mind.

The same holds true for First Bannerman, but that rank is comperable
to File Leader instead of Soldier.

A complete advancement syllabus is in the works for the near future.

-Esbjorn
</text>
